The physisorption is dominantly configured under the circumstance where the existing organic adsorbate is passivated on a metal surface. The theoretical expression on the spatial characteristics metal function reveals that the overall metal work function is governed by the bulk chemical potential (
μ ¯
) and the electrostatic potential (ϕ(x)) across the metal surface, where the electrostatic potential (ϕ(x)) mainly correlates with the combined contributions from electron density (major effect) and nucleus density [42–44]. As a consequence, the underlying work-function modulation due to the physisorption effect can be explained when the electron density tail of the metal is disturbed by the introduction of organic compounds [42,43,45]. This phenomenon originates from the push-back effect between organic/metal interfaces, when the electron density tail of the metal is pushed back into the metal atoms by Pauli repulsion. The vacuum level is lowered in this situation and the total electronic charges are transferred to the metal [43].
